data.name: bunifuLabel12.Text
data.value:
Celtic, Roman, and Germanic cultures have traditionally influenced French culture. As a result of these influences, France developed into a patchwork of regional cultures and traditions. What applies to one community might not apply to another. France has made an attempt to retain the customs of its smaller communities despite the expanding global culture of today.
Try reading books from this list or this list if you want to learn more about the nuances of French culture and communities. Or, if you're fortunate enough, you can get firsthand knowledge by exploring the French countryside.

data.name: bunifuLabel13.Text
data.value: Anatolia (the Asian portion of Turkey) and Eastern Thrace are both included in the history of Turkey, which is regarded to be the history of the area currently constituting the territory of the Republic of Turkey (the European part of Turkey). In the second century BC, the Roman Empire seized control of these two formerly independent governmental units, which later fused to form the Roman Byzantine Empire. A distinction should also be drawn between the history of the Turkic people, and the history of the regions that today make up the Republic of Turkey for eras prior to the Ottoman period. The history of Turkey includes the medieval history of the Seljuk Empire, from the period when the Seljuq dynasty acquired portions of what is now Turkey.

data.name: bunifuLabel14.Text
data.value: Italy's history spans three different time periods: antiquity, the Middle Ages, and modern times. The Italian Peninsula has been inhabited since classical antiquity by the Etruscans, numerous Italic people (such as the Latins, Samnites, and Umbri), Celts, Magna Graecia colonists, and other ancient people. Italy served as both the capital of the Roman Empire's provinces and the ancestral home of the Romans in antiquity. The Roman monarchy was abolished in favor of a government of the Senate and the People in 509 BC, and Rome was established as a republic in 753 BC. Then, at the expense of the peninsula's Etruscan, Celt, and Greek inhabitants, the Roman Republic united Italy. Socii, a union of Italic peoples, was led by Rome, and later with the rise of Rome, dominated Western Europe, Northern Africa, and the Near East.

data.name: bunifuLabel15.Text
data.value:
The phrase "Romanian culture" is used to refer to the beliefs, practices, and social interactions of the Romanian people that have emerged as a result of the country's unique geopolitical past and development. The descendants of Roman colonists and native inhabitants of the area who underwent Romanization are said to be the origins of Romanians and allied peoples (Aromanians, Megleno-Romanians, and Istro-Romanians).
One of the largest indigenous peoples in southeast Europe, the Dacians, are among the Proto-Romanians' ancestors. The current Romanians, Aromanians, Megleno-Romanians, and Istro-Romanians are thought to have descended from a mix of Dacians, Thracians, Romans, and Illyrians. Additionally, Romanian culture has a lot in common with other ancient cultures, including Armenian culture.

data.name: bunifuLabel4.Text
data.value: The first writing systems, known as Paleohispanic scripts, were formed when the pre-Roman people of the Iberian Peninsula's Mediterranean coast interacted with the Greeks and Phoenicians. The peninsula had numerous successive Greek, Carthaginian, and Roman colonizations during Classical Antiquity. Indigenous inhabitants of the peninsula, like the Tartessos people, coexisted alongside invaders to forge a distinctively Iberian culture. Spain's current name is derived from the Roman term Hispania, which was used to describe the entire Iberian Peninsula.

data.name: bunifuLabel19.Text
data.value: United Kingdom is an island nation off the coast of Europe's northwest. The entire island of Great Britain, which is made up of England, Wales, and Scotland, as well as the northern part of the island of Ireland, make up the United Kingdom. The entire United Kingdom is occasionally referred to as Britain. London, the nation's capital, is one of the top cities for business, finance, and culture in the globe. Other significant cities include Manchester, Birmingham, Liverpool, and Liverpool in England, Belfast and Londonderry in Northern Ireland, Edinburgh and Glasgow in Scotland, Swansea and Cardiff in Wales, and Edinburgh and Glasgow in Scotland.
